      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the results for the paper **\"Language Models (Mostly) Know What They Know\"** (arXiv:2207.05221):\n\n## Paper Details\n\n- **Title:** Language Models (Mostly) Know What They Know\n- **arXiv ID:** 2207.05221\n- **Published:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Submitted on 11 Jul 2022 (v1), last revised 21 Nov 2022 (this version, v4)"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Authors\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Saurav Kadavath, Tom Conerly, Amanda Askell, Tom Henighan, Dawn Drain, Ethan Perez, Nicholas Schiefer, Zac Hatfield-Dodds, Nova DasSarma, Eli Tran-Johnson, Scott Johnston, Sheer El-Showk, Andy Jones, Nelson Elhage, Tristan Hume, Anna Chen, Yuntao Bai, Sam Bowman, Stanislav Fort, Deep Ganguli, Danny Hernandez, Josh Jacobson, Jackson Kernion, Shauna Kravec, Liane Lovitt, Kamal Ndousse, Catherine Olsson, Sam Ringer, Dario Amodei, Tom Brown, Jack Clark, Nicholas Joseph, Ben Mann, Sam McCandlish, Chris Olah, and Jared Kaplan"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " (36 authors total).\n\n### Abstract Summary\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The paper studies whether language models can evaluate the validity of their own claims and predict which questions they will be able to answer correctly."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " Key findings include:\n\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Larger models are well-calibrated on diverse multiple choice and true/false questions when they are provided in the right format."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "They approach self-evaluation on open-ended sampling tasks by asking models to first propose answers, and then to evaluate the probability \"P(True)\" that their answers are correct, finding encouraging performance, calibration, and scaling for P(True) on a diverse array of tasks."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Performance at self-evaluation further improves when models are allowed to consider many of their own samples before predicting the validity of one specific possibility."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "They also investigate whether models can be trained to predict \"P(IK)\", the probability that \"I know\" the answer to a question, without reference to any particular proposed answer."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Links\n- **arXiv:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2207.05221\n- **PDF:** https://arxiv.org/pdf/2207.05221"
      }
